Name : Bhavin Bhatt¶

Title: Analysing College Student Psychology¶

Sub-title: Linear regression analysis of behaviour patterns¶

1) Objective of the Project¶

The primary aim of this research study is to leverage linear regression analysis as a tool for predicting and comprehending specific behavioral patterns among college students. Its goal is to provide valuable insights to the Psychology department of the San Francisco County Office of Education. To achieve this objective, a comprehensive survey was administered to graduate students at the University of the Pacific in San Francisco. The survey encompassed a wide array of questions related to various psychological traits, including empathy, confidence, goal orientation, social interactions, futuristic thinking, and more. The overarching purpose of this survey was to gain a deeper understanding of the thought processes and behavioral tendencies exhibited by graduate students.¶

The study aims to uncover meaningful patterns and relationships within the collected data, shedding light on how different psychological traits interplay and influence student behavior. The insights derived from this research endeavor will serve as a foundational resource for conducting further research and enhancing the counseling services offered by the San Francisco County Office of Education.¶

4) Simple Linear Regression¶

We will perform a simple linear regression with our dependent variable as below:¶

Goal-oriented column - If you have to temporarily put your plans on hold, you make sure it is your top priority to get back on track as soon as possible.¶

The purpose is to predict the behaviour amongst individuals who are more goal-oriented and how do different factors(independent variables) aid or hinder an individual's motivation to achieve goal. The following independent variables are chosen to predict the goal-oriented behaviour of a student.¶

1.Self_Assured - You rarely feel insecure.¶

2.Calm_under_pressure - You can stay calm under a lot of pressure.¶

3. Determined - You are dedicated and focused on your goals, only rarely getting sidetracked.¶

4.Pre_planner - When starting to work on a project, you prefer to make as many decisions upfront as possible.¶

5.Philosophical_thinker - You often contemplate the reasons for human existence or the meaning of life¶

6.Self_doubting - If you make a mistake, you tend to start doubting yourself, your abilities, or your knowledge¶

Model 1 - Self_Assured versus Goal-oriented¶

In [7]:
Self_assured_Model <- lm(Goal_oriented ~ Self_assured, df_final)
summary(Self_assured_Model)

library(ggplot2)
#Socially_confident
plot1 <- ggplot(data = Self_assured_Model, aes(x = Self_assured , y = Goal_oriented)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkblue", shape = 19) +
  geom_abline(intercept = Self_assured_Model$coefficients[1], slope = Self_assured_Model$coefficients[2], color = "red", linetype = "solid") +
  labs(x = "Self_assured_Model", y = "Goal_oriented") +
  ggtitle("Relationship Between Self_assured_Model and Goal_oriented") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(size = 12), axis.title = element_text(size = 14),

        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "grey"))


print(plot1)

Therefore, the Self_doubting model is less reliable for predicting Goal-oriented behavior compared to the Determined model.¶

7) Summary¶

The analysis evaluates various models for predicting Goal-oriented behavior based on different independent variables. Here are the key findings:¶

Determined Model: This model uses the "Determined" variable as an independent variable and has an R-squared value of 0.2081, indicating that approximately 20.81% of the variation in Goal-oriented behavior can be explained by determination. The p-value suggests a significant relationship between Determined and Goal-oriented, making it a reliable choice for prediction.¶

Self-doubting Model: In contrast, the model using "Self_doubting" as an independent variable performs less favorably. It has a higher p-value (0.3307) and a lower R-squared value (0.00845), indicating that Self-doubting has a minor and statistically less significant impact on Goal-oriented behavior.¶

Positive Model: This model combines multiple independent variables, including Self_assured, Calm_under_pressure, Determined, and Pre_planner, and has an R-squared value of 0.2936. These traits are positively associated with Goal-oriented behavior, explaining 29.36% of its variance.¶

Comparison between Models: When comparing the Determined Model and Positive Model, the latter is preferred due to its higher R-squared value, indicating it accounts for more variability in Goal-oriented behavior. Both models are statistically significant.¶

Negative Model: This model considers Philosopher_thinker and Self_doubting as independent variables and shows a negative relationship with Goal-oriented behavior. However, it has a low R-squared value (0.04952) and a p-value (0.05968) that suggests weak statistical significance.¶

Comparison between Negative and Philosopher_thinker Models: The Negative Model has a slightly lower p-value, suggesting a somewhat stronger statistical significance compared to the Philosopher_thinker Model. However, both models have weak explanatory power due to their low R-squared values.¶

Best Multiple Model: The best multiple linear regression model among those considered is the Positive Model, which includes Self_assured, Calm_under_pressure, Determined, and Pre_planner variables. It explains 29.36% of the variance in Goal-oriented behavior and is more comprehensive than the other models. Traits like Self_assured, Calm_under_pressure, Determined, and Pre-planner have a positive and significant effect on Goal-oriented behavior, while Self_doubting and Philosopher_thinker have a negative but relatively less significant impact.¶

8)Recommendation¶

The Positive Model, which includes Self_assured, Calm_under_pressure, Determined, and Pre_planner variables, is the most comprehensive and effective model for predicting Goal-oriented behavior. It explains a significant portion about 29.36% of the variance and provides valuable insights into the traits that contribute positively to goal achievement. Therefore, when trying to understand or predict Goal-oriented behavior, consider using this model.¶

While negative traits such as Philosopher_thinker and Self_doubting have a negative impact although very less we must avoid considering this as an individual predictor of negative impact and look at things in a whole context.¶

It is important to note that a larger dataset would have provided us a more comprehensive understanding of the behaviours among students. It is also important to know that individual behaviours are also influenced from other factors such as the social structure around individuals for example country of origin, individual experiences in life and past trauma or incidences that might affect the results. Thus in general although Positive_model gives a better understanding but we should also consider various other factors before arriving at any conclusion.¶
